text: Ella Baker said that we who believe in freedom can never rest. To those who have been doing this work, thank you for fighting for freedom‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääfor ALL of us. Happy #BlackHistoryMonth!
We must harness any privilege we have to dismantle institutions that perpetuate unjust and racist outcomes like mass incarceration, deportation and the criminalization of poverty.

Today, we have government-sanctioned hate coming from the White House and a president who equates white supremacists with civil rights protestors. In response, our work must center justice, equity and love.

The inequities of our system have resulted in centuries of tireless and inspiring organizing to bring power to those most marginalized. As an organizer myself, I am an eternal optimist who believes in what is possible when we unite and take action.
I am proud to be advancing racial justice in the halls of Congress, from supporting reparations and fair housing to co-sponsoring legislation to create equity in our economy and justice system.

Institutionalized racism is not new. Let‚Äôs be clear: This is a country built on two hundred and fifty years of slavery, 90 years of Jim Crow, 60 years of separate but equal, and more than 40 years of racist housing policy.
For those who are not the privileged few, every day is a reminder that we live in a system that has maintained itself at the expense of communities of color, especially black communities.

So excited by the incredible success of #BlackPanther! This moment, and this #BlackHistoryMonth, is an opportunity to recognize and celebrate the history of black Americans. But we must not let mere recognition be the end of our action. https://t.co/rlgOEK0NBm

My message is simple: STOP vilifying and otherizing immigrants.

Now, the local police are trying to win back the trust of immigrants and their family and friends-many of whom are U.S. citizens and fear reporting crime to the police out of fear this contact will result in the deportation of a loved one.

The local police took him to ICE because he had an ICE administrative document popped up in the system-ICE calls this a warrant, but this is misleading since there is no oversight by a third party, like a judge.
And in another case, a man in Tukwila, Washington called 911 to report a person he suspected of breaking into cars on his block.
The reason she didn't come forward to seek safety is because her abuser threatened to have her mother deported.
Just recently we saw another terrible example of what this fear is doing in our communities. We learned that a 14-year-old girl in Bellevue, Washington suffered molestation for nearly two years.

He added, "without that cooperation and trust of undocumented immigrants, we wouldn't have been able to get some dangerous offenders off the streets."

He continued, "my alarm isn't theoretical. Last year our office worked with 67 undocumented immigrants (more than 300 in the last five years) to prosecute crimes ranging from murder and rape to domestic violence."
He wrote, "we are not safer when a victim of abuse thinks she must choose between deportation or suffering more violence at the hands of her abuser. Unpunished violent crime threatens us all."
Our King County prosecutor wrote in an op-ed last year, "we are not safer when victims of crime fear being deported if they call 911, talk to police, or come to a courthouse to get protection."
This is having a real impact on our police and prosecutors who have spent years building trust with immigrant communities.

Over the last year, this administration has severely ramped up immigration enforcement across the country. In Fiscal Year 2017, ICE made 37,734 arrests of people with no criminal convictions-over twice the number from the previous year.
And when it comes to immigration, we know that eliminating community trust policies across the country will not make our communities safer.
We need to make sure law enforcement has tools to help people kick their addictions like the Law Enforcement Assisted Diversion (LEAD) Program.

Here are the facts: We know we cannot arrest our way out of the opioid crisis. What we should really focus on are the underlying causes for opiate abuse and what we can do to prevent addiction in the first place.

Alleging that deporting all 11 million undocumented immigrants will somehow fix this crisis is insulting and a slap in the face to people across the country who are depending on us to do our jobs and work on real solutions to solve a very real crisis.
This latest falsehood is outrageous. Immigrants are certainly not making the opioid crisis worse.
As an immigrant myself, I am tired of being called the worst of the worst, of hearing Mexicans called rapists and Africans called vulgarities that we aren't even allowed to say on the House floor.

Immigrants enrich our economies and communities every single day, including contributing $1.2 trillion to Social Security's Earnings Suspense File. That was at the end of 2012. The amount is presumably much larger today.

text: The State of OUR union is strong because of YOU. This democracy is OURS and we are taking it back!

We are strong when we organize and build our power, when we refuse to be intimidated or patronized, and when we give gratitude for those whose shoulders we stand on and allow others to stand on our shoulders.
We are strong when we call people IN even as we call them OUT, and recognize that it is generosity and abundance, not scarcity and fear, that always wins.
The state of OUR union is strong when fearless people stand up against tyrannical policies and do not confuse xenophobia with patriotism, or vitriol for values.

We are creating OUR union, a union that respects everyone for who we are and gives us the tools we need to thrive: good jobs so people can take care of their families, health care for all, an education without mountains of debt, retirement with dignity‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääand RESPECT.

And let me tell you‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääthey know that too! Have you seen the list of Republicans who are retiring from Congress? With women candidates, black and brown, young, transgender and immigrant‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääwe are ON THE MOVE!
I am here because we know that when we stand strong, link arms in love, organize and VOTE‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääwe are POWERFUL.
Or like Shanda, a veteran who was disabled through a horrific accident, and who nonetheless brings a deep sense of hopefulness that this country she fought for will fight for her.

People like Stephanie, who learned at 19 weeks that her pregnancy could not be brought to term and had to have an abortion‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääand as difficult as that was, she holds a deep belief that all women must be able to make the choices that are right for themselves.

People like Graciela, a Dreamer who is at risk because Donald Trump terminated the DACA program and MADE her deportable. Here in the U.S. since age 7, Graciela holds out hope every single day that she and 1.5 million other Dreamers will stop being used as political footballs.

People across our country‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääall of us‚Ää‚Äî‚Äädeserve So. Much. Better.

People like Shannon, a steelworker at a plant in Indianapolis, who supports her family through her job but has watched it move away because corporations seek cheaper labor and more profits.

It is STRONG because of millions who are watching and re-committing to a union that gets its strength from its diversity, a union that embraces those in need instead of mocking them, a union that believes in the common good, a union rooted in love and not hate.
When Donald Trump says that the state of the union is strong, I want people to know it is strong DESPITE everything he does to tear us down.

And I am increasingly convinced that this president is obstructing justice, violating the Constitution every day, benefiting from his financial interests. Every day he is enabled by the complicity of congressional Republicans, even those who KNOW that what is happening is wrong‚Ä¶

I‚Äôm done listening to more lies about standing up for workers, when every move of this administration has been to transfer wealth from workers to the top 1% in the country, strip health care from of Americans, roll-back women‚Äôs right to abortion and decimate our planet.

I am outraged by the white supremacist, anti-immigrant and racist policies that seek to make America white again.

But I am also more determined than ever.

As an immigrant, I am tired of being called the worst of the worst; I am fed up with hearing Muslims called terrorists and Mexicans called rapists; I am infuriated by scapegoating immigrants and the vulgarities used to describe entire African nations, all for political gain.

Women like them across this country, are standing up for a different kind of world‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääsisters, the future is FEMALE!

I have chosen to boycott the State of the Union because I refuse to normalize a president who foments racism and hatred to play to a shrinking part of his base.

I want to give a special thank you to the courageous and inspiring women who made this state of OUR union possible. My dear friends Ai-jen Poo and Kristin Rowe-Finkbeiner; the inspiring Tarana Burke, Cecile Richards, Monica Ramirez and Arisha Hatch.

Tonight as we mark the #StateofOURUnion, I‚Äôm so proud to be an IMMIGRANT‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääone of just a dozen or so members in the entire Congress born outside the United States‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääand someone who has spent my life as an immigrant, civil and human rights organizer, and activist. https://t.co/wPF1RE4a2u

text: Count Us In is one crucial part of those efforts - I want to thank the dedicated volunteers who walked every part of King County and I am proud to be a part of and to represent a community that cares so deeply about the vulnerable.

I will do everything I can at the federal level to build more affordable housing and fix a broken tax system that benefits only the few.¬† Solving this crisis will require all of us ‚Äîgovernment, business, nonprofits and communities ‚Äî to share responsibility for real solutions.
We can and must do better. The fact that we see thousands of people living unsheltered, in the streets and in cars, is a moral and institutional failure.

We don't know the total count yet, but we know homelessness is a local/national emergency. Walking block by block through streets booming with construction but then under the freeway in areas peppered with tents was a stark reminder of the deep inequities of wealth in our city.

Last night, my staff and I joined the @AllHomeKC annual count of people experiencing homelessness. The street count was a nearly 1000-volunteers-strong effort to canvass of all 398 census tracts in King County. https://t.co/BPloyJCays

text: Throughout the course of history, here and abroad, men and women have died to stand up against despots. Our job today is to honor those who came before us by refusing to go backward. Our job today is to stand clearly for a moral center that this president has shunned.

He does and says things that none of us, as parents, would condone for our children. He consistently uses language that is outright racist. He actively uses the highest office of the land to promote hatred as a political tool for his own benefit.

This president has consistently indicated that he has no interest in leading a unified country. He has gone out of his way to play to a small and shrinking base of voters by using language that diminishes and demeans vast swaths of people in our own country and around the world.

However, this president has gone beyond the pale, over and over again reaching new lows in his leadership of this country that I love. I hope that there will come a time soon when Republicans who I respect will also understand that to be silent is to be complicit.

My refusal to attend the State of the Union is not about policy differences‚Ää, of which I have many. I would attend a State of the Union by a president with whom I disagree if I felt she or he was otherwise respectful and adhered to basic moral values or basic tenets of civility.

As we remember and honor Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr., we remember too that if we are courageous, if we put people over politics, our actions have the power to change lives and push that moral arc of the universe more quickly towards justice.

When we lift up truth and operate from a place of generosity and abundance, that‚Äôs when we have a world that loudly proclaims that #BlackLivesMatter, that immigrants make our country strong, that #Dreamers have a place here, and that #TIMESUP on sexual harassment.
Dr. King lifted up the truth about ending segregation and discrimination. Truth about ending the war in Vietnam. Truth about lifting up sanitation workers and ending poverty.

King followed Gandhi‚Äôs principles of nonviolent resistance, also known as Satyagraha‚Äîsatya meaning truth and graha meaning adherence to or insistence upon. 

Satyagraha means an insistence on truth, and this is what Martin Luther King preached and acted upon.

But that did not stop Dr. King from speaking out, organizing and leading a growing movement that reminded the leaders of our country of the very dream that made America possible, that all men and women were created equal.

Like Gandhi, the problems that Dr. King tackled were once seen as insurmountable problems, institutional barriers of race and class that seemed as if, if taken on, would topple the tall walls of tradition and practice that kept our society segregated and divided.

text:
NAFTA renegotiation is a chance for us to bring home a win for workers. We can boost our economy, spur job growth, and protect our environment and consumers.

These things are not at odds and we have a path to make them a reality.

President Trump came into office making big promises on negotiating deals that are good for workers‚Äî but he has not.
He‚Äôs rammed through anti-worker policies and fought for a tax scam that actually doles out tax credits to the very corporations that offshore jobs.

Congress and the American people should be privy to the process. We must create seats at the table for ALL of our interests, not just corporate interests. And we need real enforcement mechanisms to defend our workers, our safety, our environment and our jobs.
None of us here are opposed to trade‚Äîyou can‚Äôt stop it any more than you can stop migration, and we wouldn‚Äôt want to. We want to build a trade deal that works for working people.
In Mexico, too, NAFTA favoritism of corporate farming ran 1.3 million Mexican farmers out of business. NAFTA has created job loss from the Midwest to Mexico, Ohio to Oaxaca.

Corporations even benefit by using  NAFTA's investor-state dispute settlement to offshore American jobs to low wage countries. Because of liberties NAFTA affords corporate giants, 930,000 American jobs have been lost under one NAFTA program alone.

text: ICYMI: I'm on @Politico's Power List for 2018 because we've worked hard this year to defend and advance civil and human rights for all, and we're only going to continue to build our mountain of resistance next year. https://t.co/JAcfMhwJxI

My heart goes out to the Newtown community. We must be working toward solutions that can save lives, and make our families and communities safer. I urge our Republican colleagues to engage with us in this dialogue that can push our country forward.

Instead of looking at commonsense solutions, the GOP passed HR 38, the Concealed Carry Reciprocity Act. It weakens concealed carry laws, allows more untrained people to carry guns, and disregards individual state laws‚Äîeven those that ban concealed guns in schools.

For example, I have cosponsored:
- HR 1612, the Gun Show Loophole Closing Act
- HR 1478, the Gun Violence Research Act
- HR 2670, the Protecting Domestic Violence and Stalking Victims Act
- HR 3947 Automatic Gunfire Prevention Act to prohibit the use of bump stocks
We have proposed solutions, but we need to work across the aisle. Now is the time to come together. But Republican leadership won't bring commonsense gun bills to a vote.

And every time we send thoughts and prayers, but fail to act, we are simply waiting for the next mass shooting. Since Sandy Hook, we have seen shootings in Charleston, San Bernardino, Orlando, Las Vegas and Sutherland Springs take the lives of 156 innocent people.

We have watched Republicans block responsible bill after responsible bill. We've been told by colleagues across the aisle that we shouldn‚Äôt politicize tragedy. But talking about solutions is not politicizing. It is prevention.

After this community experienced unthinkable loss, we stood together and said ‚Äúno more.‚Äù Yet, what has changed? Since Sandy Hook, there have been more than 1,500 mass shootings. Nearly 1,800 people have lost their lives. More than 6,200 people have been wounded.

Today marks five years since a gunman murdered 26 members of Newtown‚Äôs community, including 20 first and second grade children. Today, we remember the victims and survivors of the Sandy Hook shooting. https://t.co/EkFHTI5wWd

The internet is not just the internet‚Äîthe push to #ProtectNetNeutrality is about our democracy.

@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit @RepMcEachin @RepBarragan No great movement has ever been easy. The fight for our climate, our jobs and our rights will be tough. But when we join forces, we win.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit @RepMcEachin @RepBarragan Our movement is strong, but we'll build more strength by not only calling people out, but by calling them in to find common ground.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit It's also why @RepMcEachin, @RepBarragan and I created the Environmental Justice Task Force. Climate policy should be justice-focused.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit That's why I co-sponsored a bill to get the U.S. to 100 percent renewable energy by 2050. The #100by50 Act lays out a path for our future.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit ...we must also propose the vision of what we want the world to look like. We must be a proposition party that puts ideas into action.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit And as we oppose the stripping of environmental regulations, the disregard for people of color and policies that are bad for workers‚Ä¶
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit We must fight the rules that allow big business to profit at the expense of our communities and our climate. We must oppose climate deniers.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit So, we need to lengthen the decision-making table to ensure space for communities of color, environmental leaders AND organized labor.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit Though it is more complex to build coalitions and find solutions that work for everyone, the most surefire way to lose is to go it alone.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit From collective bargaining to a fair minimum wage to clean energy and jobs transition - we fight together so we all rise together.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit We can't be fooled by false choices. It is not jobs OR environment; economy OR morality. We must defend all these things all the time.
@climatesolution @BGAlliance @CFESummit The strongest movements are built when we join together‚Äîat the intersections of labor, environment, jobs and organizing, we find our power.

text: @CAPAC AAPI voices are critical in this fight. Now, we must pass the DREAM Act so that people like Amy can continue to access the American dream.

text: About 3,000 people called and tuned in to the tele-town hall this evening. Grateful to represent such a strongly engaged district!
And with that, thank you so much to everyone for the thoughtful questions and comments! More tele-townhalls to come!
A (cont'd): We need to lead from a place of abundance and generosity, with safety nets for people going through hard times.
A: Time and time again, we've pushed back. We need to have deep compassion and respect for those who are differently abled.
Comment from Raymond in Burien: I believe in Medicare and Medicaid. Trump says people need to work - some are disabled and cannot work!
A (cont'd): If someone is qualified to serve, it doesn't matter who they are. There's bipartisan opposition and we'll keep fighting it.
A: Mattis didn't even know about the ban when it was handed down. I've been disgusted. Trump throwing red meat to a tiny part of his base.
Q from Edmonds: What do we do about Trump's transgender military ban? I know someone in the military who is affected and fearful.
A (cont'd): Also - we need fair budgets that invest in people, support vets. It's clear that trickle-down economics have been a failure.
A: We are seeing all the effects of climate change - one of my top issues. 100% renewable energy by 2050 is an achievable goal.
Q from Rita in Edmonds: What can be done about more storms, more crises, threats from N. Korea?
A (cont'd): It's not that this can't be done. Every major developed country has a system like this one. We're building momentum.
Today I talked to Luis, a Dreamer with @UNITEDWEDREAM. He is worried about his future and his little brother. Please listen and share. https://t.co/wy4lmkfya6
A: I'm a longtime supporter of single payer. Co-sponsoring the Conyers #MedicareforAll bill. Also working to free up states to pursue it.
Q from Seattle: When do we get single payer healthcare? Why do Congress members get better healthcare than constituents?
A (2/2): We need to all work to preserve opportunity for all to lead decent lives - and make sure corporations are paying their fair share.
A (1/2): Deal struck with GOP yesterday preserves leverage over next 3 months for minority to act on healthcare and DREAM Act and more.
Q: We're all human beings - how do we organize together to make our views on what is going on loud and clear?
A: It's terrible and you've articulated the deep emotional trauma that people are going through. Deporting DREAMers is untenable.
Q from Seattle: My Hispanic family is worried. Children are in school, family members are working. What happens if they are sent away?
A: I led voter reg. drives as OneAmerica director. We must resist voter suppression, and we need candidates that reflect our communities.
Q from Diane in Lake Forest Park: How can we help minority communities vote in elections so their interests are protected?
A: Our immigration system is broken - it's not so simple. Worked for 15 yrs from the outside to fix it, and we're going to keep on pushing.
Q from Shoreline: Why can't DREAMers simply use the traditional or typical path to become citizens?
A: It was not unconstitutional, but now we are in a situation where Congress needs to act. Appreciate your support for the DREAM Act!
Q from Robert in Edmonds, who says he supports Trump as well as the 2017 DREAM Act: Was Obama's DACA directive unconstitutional?
A: Does GOP want to throw out DREAMers? Their base is actually against it, including much of the Trump base. We have momentum and leverage.
Second Q, coming from Vashon: There has been plenty of bipartisan support for DREAMers - what happened to that and how do we pass a bill?
A: Open to compromise. 2013 immigration bill had some bad aspects, but accomplished greater good. But hopeful about a clean DACA bill.
